Scotland’s private schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another collection of outstanding exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community subjects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired topic within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it comes to his mind.
But if you speak to him in your own language, come to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the recent exams this year, we can see that languages are at the highest on the board and with the highest approved rates in private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages received an outstanding score.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained honorary enrollment in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding one.
This demonstrates that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are taking the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private school programs of all kinds.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Training in 2014 found that among the lack of language skills, it constitutes 17% of the reasons why employers find it difficult to cover vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more job opportunities that need languages.
Regardless of the chosen career, learning a second language will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will put a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
That’s why it’s so important to invest in a language for today’s kids.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing economies, provides children with more opportunities to find a meaningful job.
In Scotland, the language of instruction differs according to the school.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others opt for languages considered more important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of what the interests of their children are, private schools always have several languages to choose from and specialized teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialize in providing a learning environment that prepares children and staff with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
We cannot deny that at this time, in a global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edwards is the director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
