North Korea says no to unilateral disarmament if there is no confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions increased its distrust of the United States and that the country would not hand over its nuclear weapons in those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important steps to show its goodwill" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test camps and committing to the proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see the corresponding response from the United States," he added.
"Without confidence in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and, in such circumstances, there will be unilateral disarmament first on our part."
While Ri resumed the already known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to “gradual” denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as it did not reject unilateral denuclearization as it did with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to “denuclearize” the Korean peninsula while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted loosening the harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal of coercive object, and even oppose the ‘declaration of the end of war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us sneeze is an impossible dream for someone who doesn’t know us.
But the problem is that continuing sanctions exacerbate our distrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the other part of this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached a dead end."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after the “evil president” Trump called Kim a “man rocket on a suicide mission.”
This year at the U.N., Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking action to disarm, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
Trump said there was no deadline for that, and that "it would take two years, three or five months."
China and Russia discuss whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
