Lieutenant Colonel and Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded on September 29, 1918, in the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later without knowing that he was awarded the highest British military decoration.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren were tasked with discovering a memorial in his honor at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
Michael Vann, one of his grandsons, emphasized the symbolism of discovering this monument just 100 years after his grandmother’s masterpiece earned him the title.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann directed his battalion through the Saint-Quentin canal "through a dense fog and under the yoke of an intense machine gun fire".
He later rushed to reach the line of fire and, with "great courage", directed the line forward before rushing with a cannon and without the help of anyone, and shot down three people from the enemy detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just a month before the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandmother's actions were "something he could never live with, but a lesson still like that."
He and his brother Dr James Vann also placed a flower crown after the parade, which led the youth band Brentwood Imperial.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to participate in the parade" and added that "the courage of this genuine hero demonstrates the support of so many people."
