Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the latest report by the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Conservation Commission, there is a general reduction in red tidal concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the above-mentioned commission, increasingly unequal breeding conditions are being observed in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, which may mean that concentrations are being reduced.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Concentrations may be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsboroug County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
It was reported that there were medium-level concentrations on the coast or away from the coast of Pinellas County last week, background and elevated concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background and elevated concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No cases of this type have been reported in Northwest Florida over the past week.
